<p>Most motor boat owners have a rough sense that a dirty hull burns more fuel. It's one of those things people "know" without ever putting numbers to it. But when you actually calculate the cost, the figures are surprisingly stark — and they make the case for regular hull cleaning purely on financial grounds, before you even consider performance or paint preservation.</p>

<h2>The Physics in 30 Seconds</h2>

<p>A boat moves through water. The water resists that movement. That resistance is called drag. There are two types of drag that matter here: form drag (the shape of the hull pushing water aside) and skin friction drag (the water flowing across the hull's surface).</p>

<p>Skin friction accounts for roughly 60-80% of total resistance on a displacement hull at typical cruising speeds. That means the condition of your hull's surface — how smooth or rough it is — directly affects the majority of the resistance your engine has to overcome.</p>

<p>When marine organisms colonise your hull, they increase surface roughness dramatically. Even a light biofilm (that barely-visible slime layer) measurably increases roughness. Barnacles, tubeworms, and macroalgae increase it far more. The rougher the surface, the more turbulent the boundary layer, the higher the skin friction, and the more fuel your engine burns to maintain any given speed.</p>

<h2>The Numbers</h2>

<p>Research from multiple independent sources gives us reliable data on the relationship between fouling and fuel consumption:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Light biofilm (slime only):</strong> 10-16% increase in frictional resistance. On a motor cruiser burning 20 litres per hour at cruise, that's 2-3 extra litres per hour.</li>
  <li><strong>Moderate fouling (established algae + early barnacles):</strong> 20-30% increase in resistance. That's 4-6 extra litres per hour on the same vessel.</li>
  <li><strong>Heavy fouling (mature barnacle community):</strong> 40-60% increase in resistance. At this level, performance degradation is obvious even to a casual operator — the boat feels sluggish, slow to plane, and drinks fuel at an alarming rate.</li>
</ul>

<h2>A Real-World Example</h2>

<p>Let's work through a practical example for a 15-metre motor cruiser based in Torquay — a common vessel type in the English Riviera's premium marina.</p>

<p>At clean-hull cruise speed (let's say 18 knots), this vessel burns approximately 45 litres of diesel per hour. At current UK marina diesel prices of around £1.85-2.00 per litre, that's roughly £85 per hour in fuel.</p>

<p>With moderate fouling accumulated over 4-5 months without cleaning, that same vessel now faces a 25% increase in fuel consumption to maintain the same speed. That's an extra 11 litres per hour — approximately £21 per hour wasted.</p>

<p>If this boat is used for 120 hours during the season (a fairly average figure for a regularly-used motor yacht), the total fuel waste from fouling amounts to roughly £2,500 over the season. That's not a rounding error. That's the cost of a full set of hull maintenance for the year, several times over.</p>

<p>Even taking the most conservative estimate — light biofilm producing only a 10% increase — the numbers still favour cleaning. A 10% increase on 45 litres/hour is 4.5 extra litres per hour, or about £9 wasted per running hour. Over 120 hours, that's £1,080 in unnecessary fuel expenditure.</p>

<h2>Sailing Yachts Are Affected Too</h2>

<p>Motor vessel owners tend to notice the fuel impact first because they're watching the fuel gauge. But sailing yachts are equally affected — the drag just manifests differently.</p>

<p>A fouled hull on a sailing yacht reduces speed through the water for any given wind strength. In a 12-knot breeze, a clean 36-footer might make 6.5 knots. The same boat with moderate fouling might only make 5.5 knots. That's nearly a knot of lost speed — the difference between arriving at your destination anchorage comfortably before dark and motoring the last hour on the iron topsail.</p>

<p>For racing sailors, the impact is even more acute. Competitive yacht racing is won and lost by seconds per mile. Even light biofilm creates a measurable speed disadvantage. It's why serious racing crews clean their hulls before every significant event.</p>

<h2>The Cleaning Cost vs Fuel Saving</h2>

<p>Here's where the maths becomes unanswerable. Four robotic hull cleans per year on a 15-metre motor yacht costs £900 at our standard rate, or £765 on an Essential subscription plan. The fuel saving from maintaining a clean hull — even using the most conservative 10% figure — exceeds £1,000 per year for a reasonably active motor vessel.</p>

<p>In other words, regular hull cleaning doesn't cost you money. It saves you money. The cleaning pays for itself in fuel savings alone, before you factor in the additional benefits of preserved antifouling, better performance, and proper hull documentation.</p>

<p>That's not a sales pitch. It's arithmetic.</p>

